  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4171966105" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4171966105" />
    <a title="Dunigan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/40859577-dunigan"><img alt="Dunigan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1611342033p2/40859577.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4171966105?book_show_action=true">Aug 31, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Dunigan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Dunigan" href="/user/show/40859577-dunigan">Dunigan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4171966105" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6673138002834657521">A pleasurable read about an old man living in the Ecuadorian jungle with a love for romance novels. But were not talking about just any old romance novels—Antonio José Bolívar likes the kind of romance novels that make your lungs black; that tear your heart out and leave you to pick up the pieces; the kind that may leave you feeling a little lonelier than you felt before you started. Antonio wants the books he reads to HURT.<br/><br/>While Antonio likes these kinds of books, The Old Man Who Read Love Stor</span>
  <span id="freeText6673138002834657521" style="display:none">A pleasurable read about an old man living in the Ecuadorian jungle with a love for romance novels. But were not talking about just any old romance novels—Antonio José Bolívar likes the kind of romance novels that make your lungs black; that tear your heart out and leave you to pick up the pieces; the kind that may leave you feeling a little lonelier than you felt before you started. Antonio wants the books he reads to HURT.<br /><br />While Antonio likes these kinds of books, The Old Man Who Read Love Stories book did none of these things to me (any blackness of my lungs is from my own doing, and can't be blamed on the book, unfortunately!!!). One reason it didn't leave me heartbroken is that it isn't a love story. It is just the story of a man who loves to read and keeps getting fucking interrupted by the fat, slovenly, d-bag mayor of his town, whom I pictured in my head as some sort of anthropomorphized bag of spoiled milk (picture the Kool-Aid man, only uglier, less fit, and even less charismatic). Along with the milk-bag mayor, there are a bunch of white, colonialist, gold-hunting Mr. Jones's who also pop up in the town from time to time and demand that 80-some-year-old Antonio take them into the jungle because Antonio is the wisest guy around when it comes to matters of the wilderness. Of course, these "explorers" don't give a damn about Antonio's desire to do nothing more than sit and read love stories for the remainder of his days on this planet, and so they coerce him into helping. It's a testament to Antonio's reputation as a jungle explorer that these gold hunters apparently have no apprehension about heading into the jungle with old man Antonio, who I can only imagine looked like a walking corpse. <br /><br />A lot of the book takes place during one of these adventures where Antonio, the mayor , and some explorers are trying to hunt down a wild animal that's been causing all sorts of trouble (and by trouble I mean it was eating people). The wild animal, however, is only angry because the explorers have been fucking up it's life (big surprise!!!). Antonio knows this, so he has a certain amount of respect for the animal, and this makes their final show down all the more rewarding. Another really interesting part of the book is the flashback to Antonio as a younger man, and you get to see his origin story (like all good heroes, it involves a lot of heartbreak) and how he found his love for romance stories.<br /><br />A part of me obviously hated the mayor and all the explorers for constantly hounding Antonio when all the guy wanted to do was READ. Yet, I also couldn't help but feel that Antonio's life was a little more full for having gone on these adventures—but still, screw those guys. I think there's a tension in everyone who enjoys reading like Antonio does—there's the draw to the rich internal life that reading good novels bring about, but then there is also the "real world" out there, begging to be reveled in. Finding the balance between the two is difficult, and it's easy to get so absorbed in the world of fiction that you forget about the world out there, and don't actually experience anything new. To be fair, Antonio is clearly inches from the grave, and so he's probably seen enough of what life has to offer to be able to confidently conclude that he's fine to sit in the world of fiction for his twilight years. Someone like me, on the other hand, needs to be a little more careful how much time he spends buried in between the pages of a novel, and I think part of why I liked this book as much as I did is that it made me think about this a more than I otherwise would have.<br /><br />It's a pretty short read. It's not gonna change your life. If you're looking to broaden your reading horizons to some South American literature, this wouldn't be your worst choice, but read some Garcia Marquez first.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6673138002834657521" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

