  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3359968851" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3359968851" />
    <a title="Cristi Ivan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/93976803-cristi-ivan"><img alt="Cristi Ivan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1615044221p2/93976803.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3359968851?book_show_action=true">May 29, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Cristi Ivan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Cristi Ivan" href="/user/show/93976803-cristi-ivan">Cristi Ivan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3359968851" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7170480076193495034"><b> The Old Man Who Read Love Stories</b> by Luis Sepulveda is an astonishing tale of solitude of a man who only dreams of love. At the same time, it’s an ode to nature and the way we should live our life in perfect harmony with it. <br/><br/>Antonio Jose Bolivar is an old man who lives alone in a small Ecuadorian village, right at the edge of the Amazonian jungle, on the bank of Nangaritza river. He came from the mountains, long ago, together with his wife, Dolores Encarnacion del Santisimo Sacramento Estupinan</span>
  <span id="freeText7170480076193495034" style="display:none"><b> The Old Man Who Read Love Stories</b> by Luis Sepulveda is an astonishing tale of solitude of a man who only dreams of love. At the same time, it’s an ode to nature and the way we should live our life in perfect harmony with it. <br /><br />Antonio Jose Bolivar is an old man who lives alone in a small Ecuadorian village, right at the edge of the Amazonian jungle, on the bank of Nangaritza river. He came from the mountains, long ago, together with his wife, Dolores Encarnacion del Santisimo Sacramento Estupinan Otavalo. <br /><br />All the way through the book, the author always uses Dolores’ full name and although it gave the novel a slightly comic note, its initials are a little bit too close to the Spanish word <b>deseo</b>. And this book is about yearning, the desire to find true, passionate love, to bring back the natural balance of the environment, that has long been tainted by the Western civilization.<br /><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[After the death of his wife,  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>Antonio Jose Bolivar starts to spend more and more time with the indigenous population of Shuars, learning to live in good harmony with the nature. Now old, his only joy in life is the arrival of the dentist, twice a year, who brings him two books each time, recommended by a prostitute.<br /><br />Antonio Jose Bolivar's desire for love is reflected in the heartbreaking story of the female jaguar, whose cubs and pairs are killed by a gold prospector. The female jaguar and Antonio’s fate intertwine throughout the novel, reaching a tragic conclusion.<br /><br />The writing style is marvelous. While reading this novel, I felt a constant coldness and humidity. On the background of my thoughts, I heard the constant sound of rain falling on the leaves of the Ecuadorian rainforest. It was beautiful and I really recommend this novel!</span>
  <a data-text-id="7170480076193495034" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

